I would take a different approach altogether.

For clicking, i would want two methods - WaitForControlToBeClickable and Click.

The first method is to make sure the element is visible. This can get reused in all your other action methods you will need. 

```
  static bool WaitForControlToBeClickable(By SeleniumObject, int waitFor = 10)
        {
            try
            {
                WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(waitFor));
                wait.Until(SeleniumExtras.WaitHelpers.ExpectedConditions.ElementIsVisible(SeleniumObject));
                return true;
            }
            catch (Exception er)
            {
                return false;
                throw er;
            }

        }
```

Next you&#39;ll make a method to click and call the previous method inside:
```
        public void Click(By SeleniumObject)
        {
            WaitForControlClickable(SeleniumObject);
            driver.FindElement(SeleniumObject).Click();
        }
```

You can store these in another class - CommonActions. So once you instantiate that in your test you can call it like this:
```
commonAction.Click(MyObject);
```

I also recommend storing your objects in an object repository separately that you call with your actions to create tests.

