Assuming the numbers are all at the start of lines, use

    &#39;~^\d{5}\b~m&#39;
    &#39;~^\d{5}(?!\d)~m&#39;
    &#39;~^\d{5}(?=\|)~m&#39;

The regexps match start of lines (with `^`, due to `m` it matches line start), then 5 digits (with `\d{5}`) and then either a word boundary (with `\b`), a position not immediately followed with a digit (with the `(?!\d)` negative lookahead) or a location immediately followed with a `|` char (with the `(?=\|)` positive lookahead).

See the [PHP demo][1]:

    $string =&#39;
    10822|~0-0
    10827|~0-0
    10990|~0-0
    11538|~0-0
    11365|~0-0&#39;;
    if (preg_match_all(&#39;~^\d{5}\b~m&#39;, $string, $matches)) {
        print_r($matches[0]);
    }
    // =&gt; Array ( [0] =&gt; 10822 [1] =&gt; 10827 [2] =&gt; 10990 [3] =&gt; 11538 [4] =&gt; 11365 )


